As illustrated in Figure 8, the algorithm in [14] initially carries out traditional time bisection to find two transition times for the data, \${\rm t}_{{\rm H}1}\$ and \${\rm t}_{{\rm L}1}\$ such that:

•
The synchronizer output settles high for a rising input transition at time \${\rm t}_{{\rm H}1}\$;
•
The synchronizer output settles low for a rising input transition at time \${\rm t}_{{\rm L}1}\$;
•
\${\rm t}_{{\rm L}1}-{\rm t}_{{\rm H}1}\$ is sufficiently small so that linear interpolation can be used to accurately determine the behavior of the synchronizer for input transition times in the interval \$[{\rm t}_{{\rm L}1}, {\rm t}_{{\rm H}1}]\$;
•
\${\rm t}_{{\rm L}1}-{\rm t}_{{\rm H}1}\$ is sufficiently large so that the simulation results for input transitions times \${\rm t}_{{\rm L}1}\$ and \${\rm t}_{{\rm H}1}\$ differ by much more than the numerical error of the simulator.

